16253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116253"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents with a four day history of left shoulder pain. He works as a janitor and reports pain when he mops the floor. The pain is worse with repeated shoulder movements during mopping and is relieved with ibuprofen and rest. On examination, there is left shoulder tenderness when his hands are placed overhead. Similar pain is reproduced on the empty can test.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely injured within the shoulder joint?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supraspinatus tendon","Teres minor tendon","Infraspinatus tendon","Glenohumeral joint capsule","Subscapularis tendon"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERotator cuff tendons are common sources of shoulder pain, particularly with overhead and repetitive activity. The empty can test (shoulder flexion in the scapular plane to about 90 degrees with internal rotation and resisted abduction) isolates the supraspinatus; pain or weakness suggests supraspinatus pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupraspinatus tendon\u003C/strong\u003E is best assessed by the empty can test; this patient\u2019s pain reproduced by this manoeuvre makes supraspinatus injury most likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETeres minor tendon\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to external rotation, particularly in the abducted position; weakness or pain on resisted external rotation in abduction supports teres minor involvement rather than a positive empty can sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfraspinatus tendon\u003C/strong\u003E is a primary external rotator of the shoulder and is assessed by resisted external rotation with the elbow flexed at 90 degrees by the side. Pain or weakness on external rotation against resistance suggests infraspinatus involvement, not a positive empty can test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlenohumeral joint capsule\u003C/strong\u003E pathology presents with instability or global stiffness; the anterior apprehension test evaluates anterior instability and is not the pattern described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubscapularis tendon\u003C/strong\u003E is the main internal rotator and can be assessed by the lift-off or belly-press tests; pain or weakness on these indicates subscapularis involvement rather than an isolated positive empty can test.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pain on the empty can test suggests supraspinatus tendon injury."],"references":["Reider B. Physical examination. Am J Sports Med 2004; 32:299."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98249"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11509"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98249"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T20:54:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T20:57:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4140"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116253"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ